Also a reminder that O(n) v/s O(n) v/s O(nlogn) is not too significant when dealing with small arrays (~50) and doing things in memory. Nano/pico seconds.

The minute you add I/O (like a query over network), suddenly it’s milliseconds per iteration, so O(n) is expensive.
